            <pb n="2" facs="#f0001"/>
            <div n="1">
                <head>
                    <hi rendition="#k">Universal Diffusion of Life.</hi>
                </head>
                <p>&#x2014;Since the time<lb break="yes"/>when, in an earlier work,
                    (&#x201C;Ansichten der Natur,&#x201D;<lb break="yes"/>&#x201C;Tableaux de la
                    Nature,&#x201D;) I attempted to describe<lb break="yes"/>the universal diffusion
                    of organic life on the surface of<lb break="yes"/>the globe, and its
                    distribution in height and in depth,<lb break="yes"/>our knowledge has been
                    wonderfully augmented by<lb break="yes"/>Ehrenberg&#x2019;s
                            <choice><sic>brillinnt</sic><corr type="editorial"
                        >brilliant</corr></choice> discoveries, (&#x201C;über das Verhal-<lb
                        break="no"/>ten des kleinsten Lebens in dem Weltmeere wie in<lb break="yes"
                    />dem Eise der <choice><sic>Polar länder</sic><corr type="editorial"
                            >Polarländer</corr></choice>,&#x201D;) which rest not on ingeni-<lb
                        break="no"/>ous combinations and inferences, but on direct and<lb
                        break="yes"/>exact observation. By these discoveries the sphere of<lb
                        break="yes"/>animated existence&#x2014;we may say the horizon of
                        life&#x2014;<lb break="yes"/>has expanded before our view. &#x201C;Not only
                    is there no<lb break="yes"/>interruption of minute microscopic forms of
                        animal<lb break="yes"/>life in the vicinity of either Pole, where larger
                        animals<lb break="yes"/>cannot maintain themselves, but we find among the<lb
                        break="yes"/>microscopic animals of the South Polar Seas, collected<lb
                        break="yes"/>in the Antarctic expedition of Captain James Ross,<lb
                        break="yes"/>a remarkable abundance of new forms, which are<lb break="yes"
                    />often of great elegance. Even in the residuum<lb break="yes"/>obtained from
                    melted ice which floats in rounded<lb break="yes"/>fragments in latitude 78 deg.
                    10 min. S., there have<lb break="yes"/>been found above fifty species of
                    siliceous-shelled poly-<lb break="no"/>gastrica, and even coscinodisc&#x00E6;
                    with green ovaries,<lb break="yes"/>which were therefore certainly living and
                    able to resist<lb break="yes"/>the extreme severity of the cold.&#x201D; * *
                        *<lb break="yes"/>It is not only in particular localities, in inland
                        waters,<lb break="yes"/>or in the vicinity of coasts, that the ocean is thus
                        thickly<lb break="yes"/>peopled with living atoms invisible to the naked
                        eye.<lb break="yes"/>Samples of water taken up by Schayer in 57 deg. S.<lb
                        break="yes"/>latitude, on his return from Van Diemen Island, as<lb
                        break="yes"/>well as those taken between the Tropics in the middle<lb
                        break="yes"/>of the Atlantic, show that the ocean water in its ordi-<lb
                        break="no"/>nary condition, without any appearance of discoloura-<lb
                        break="no"/>tion, contains innumerable microscopic organisms,<lb break="yes"
                    />quite distinct from the siliceous filaments of the genus<lb break="yes"
                    />ch&#x00E6;toceros, floating in a fragmentary state like the<lb break="yes"
                    />oscillatoria of our fresh waters. Some polygastrica<lb break="yes"/>which have
                    been found mixed with sand and exerements<lb break="yes"/>of penguins in the
                    Cockburn Islands, appear to be gene-<lb break="no"/>rally distributed over the
                    globe; other species belong to<lb break="yes"/>both the Artic and Antarctic
                    Polar regions. Thus we<lb break="yes"/>see that animal life reigns in the
                    perpetual night of the<lb break="yes"/>depths of the ocean; while on continents,
                        vegetable<lb break="yes"/>life, stimulated by the periodical action of the
                    solar rays,<lb break="yes"/>chiefly predominates. * * * * * * Not only<lb
                        break="yes"/>are earth, air, and water, filled with life, and that at<lb
                        break="yes"/>the most different temperatures, but also the interior<lb
                        break="yes"/>of the various parts of animal bodies: there are<lb break="yes"
                    />animalcula in the blood of frogs and of salmon: ac-<lb break="no"/>cording to
                    Nordmann, the fluids of the eyes of fishes<lb break="yes"/>are often filled with
                    a worm which lives by suction<lb break="yes"/>(diplostomum); and the same
                    naturalist has even dis-<lb break="no"/>covered in the gills of the bleak an
                        extraordinary<lb break="yes"/>double animal (diplozon paradoxon) having two
                        heads<lb break="yes"/>and two caudal extremities disposed in rectangular<lb
                        break="yes"/>directions.&#x2014;<hi rendition="#i">Humboldt&#x2019;s
                        Cosmos.</hi>
                </p>
